            <h2 id="why-pdfs-are-hard">Why PDFs Are Hard to Convert Accurately</h2>
            <p>The core problem is that PDFs and Word documents store content completely differently.</p>
            <p>A Word document stores content as flowing text — paragraphs, styles, headings — with a document structure that Word understands. A PDF stores content as absolute positioned elements on a page — every character, line, and image has an X/Y coordinate. There's no concept of "paragraph" or "heading" in a PDF. Just elements placed at specific positions.</p>
            <p>When you convert a PDF to Word, the converter has to reverse-engineer the document structure from those positioned elements. It has to guess: "These characters at similar Y positions are probably the same line. These lines with extra spacing are probably headings. These positioned blocks are probably a table."</p>
            <p>That reverse-engineering is where formatting breaks.</p>

            <div class="article-callout article-callout--orange">
                <strong>The key insight:</strong> PDF to Word conversion quality depends almost entirely on how the original PDF was created — not on which conversion tool you use. A text-based PDF from Word or InDesign converts very well. A scanned paper document converts poorly without OCR.
            </div>

            <h2 id="types-of-pdfs">The 3 Types of PDFs and Their Conversion Quality</h2>

            <div class="article-grid-3">
                <div class="article-level-card article-level--green">
                    <div class="article-level-label">Type 1: Text PDF</div>
                    <div class="article-level-reduction">90–98% accurate</div>
                    <p>Created from Word, InDesign, or another digital tool. Text is selectable and searchable. Converts with excellent formatting fidelity for most document types.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-level-card article-level--yellow">
                    <div class="article-level-label">Type 2: Mixed PDF</div>
                    <div class="article-level-reduction">60–85% accurate</div>
                    <p>Mostly digital text with some scanned elements, complex multi-column layouts, or embedded charts. Accuracy varies significantly by document complexity.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="article-level-card article-level--red">
                    <div class="article-level-label">Type 3: Scanned PDF</div>
                    <div class="article-level-reduction">40–75% accurate</div>
                    <p>A photo or scan of a paper document. Requires OCR to extract text. Accuracy depends on scan quality, font legibility, and OCR engine quality.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p>To check what type your PDF is: try selecting text with your cursor. If you can select and copy text, it's a Type 1 or 2. If you can't select any text, it's a scanned (Type 3) PDF.</p>

