            <h2 id="how-to-improve">How to Improve Conversion Quality</h2>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">1</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Start with the highest-quality source PDF possible</strong>
                    <p>If you have access to the original Word or InDesign file, convert directly from that rather than from a PDF. The "convert back from PDF" step introduces unnecessary quality loss.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">2</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Use OCR for scanned documents</strong>
                    <p>If your PDF is a scan, run it through PdfToolStack's <a href="/pdf-ocr">OCR tool</a> first to make the text machine-readable, then convert to Word. The OCR step dramatically improves conversion accuracy for scanned documents.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">3</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Break complex documents into sections</strong>
                    <p>If a 50-page document has complex multi-column sections mixed with simple text sections, split it first. Convert the simple sections and the complex sections separately, then reassemble in Word. You'll get better results than converting the whole document at once.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">4</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Use "Find and Replace" in Word after converting</strong>
                    <p>A common issue after PDF-to-Word conversion is that paragraph breaks appear mid-sentence due to how lines are detected. In Word, use Find &amp; Replace with wildcards to clean up unwanted line breaks.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">5</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Reapply Word styles after converting</strong>
                    <p>Even if headings look correct visually, they may not have the proper Heading 1/2/3 styles applied. Using Word styles ensures the document works correctly with table of contents, navigation, and accessibility features.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

