            <h2 id="after-conversion">What to Fix After Converting</h2>
            <p>Even with excellent conversion, most PDF-to-Word documents need some cleanup. Here's a quick post-conversion checklist:</p>

            <div class="article-checklist">
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Check for run-on sentences from merged lines</strong><p>Scan through the document for sentences where words run together without spaces, particularly at line breaks.</p></div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Verify table structure</strong><p>Click inside each table and confirm rows and columns are intact. Complex tables often need manual fixing.</p></div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Reapply heading styles</strong><p>Visually confirm headings, then use Word's Styles panel to apply the correct Heading 1/2/3 styles.</p></div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Check page breaks</strong><p>PDF page breaks don't always translate to Word page breaks cleanly. Review and adjust manually.</p></div></div>
                <div class="article-check"><span>✓</span><div><strong>Update headers and footers</strong><p>If the PDF had headers/footers, they likely converted as body text. Move them to proper Word header/footer sections.</p></div></div>
            </div>

